So, please don't try to drag it out of me?

241
00:16:10,705 --> 00:16:14,501
- Ok, no problem. I'll see ya.
- It's about my wife, if you must know.

242
00:16:14,606 --> 00:16:18,101
Well, I don't must know,
so if you'd rather not talk about it...

243
00:16:18,206 --> 00:16:19,501
Thank you. I feel so much better.

244
00:16:19,606 --> 00:16:23,603
Now, what can I do for you,
Melinda Gordon?

245
00:16:23,705 --> 00:16:27,703
Do you have any idea
what these numbers mean?

246
00:16:27,808 --> 00:16:31,900
- 1 9 0 2 0 6. Map coordinates?
- Checked it already. Doesn't add up.

247
00:16:32,006 --> 00:16:35,503
Well, it adds up in numerology to... 9.

248
00:16:35,608 --> 00:16:37,102
- Meaning?
- Meaning 9.

249
00:16:37,208 --> 00:16:40,401
9 is the divine number, the number
of completion, the eternal number.

250
00:16:40,506 --> 00:16:42,600
The chinese considered it
the celestial number.

251
00:16:42,705 --> 00:16:46,900
And there's the famous 9 course meal
at my favorite vietnamese restaurant,
beef or fish.

252
00:16:47,006 --> 00:16:49,403
-  Is any of this helping you?
- Not really.

253
00:16:49,506 --> 00:16:52,003
Of course not. Because none of this
has anything to do with numerology.

254
00:16:52,106 --> 00:16:53,701
- It doesn't?
- No, it doesn't.

255
00:16:53,807 --> 00:17:00,801
But that doesn't stop me from going on
and on with all the minutiae I know,
does it?

256
00:17:03,608 --> 00:17:05,302
- It's a date!
- It's a date.

257
00:17:05,406 --> 00:17:07,600
Challenge me next time
you come in here, won't you?

258
00:17:07,707 --> 00:17:11,600
19th of february, 2006.
That's a year ago next monday.

259
00:17:11,705 --> 00:17:16,101
It's a significant date. February 19,
1945 was the battle of Iwo Jima.

260
00:17:16,208 --> 00:17:18,703
The phonograph was invented in 1878.

261
00:17:18,808 --> 00:17:23,400
Paul Simon writes "Sounds of Silence"
1964, february 19.

262
00:17:23,505 --> 00:17:26,802
Big makeout song for me.

263
00:17:26,906 --> 00:17:27,801
How do you know all that?

264
00:17:27,908 --> 00:17:29,501
Well, while the other kids
were out playing baseball...

265
00:17:29,607 --> 00:17:31,802
- You were studying.
- No. I was chasing girls.

266
00:17:31,908 --> 00:17:35,801
I never had to study.
Studying I never did because
knowledge came so easy to me.

267
00:17:35,907 --> 00:17:37,103
Girls, not so much.

268
00:17:37,207 --> 00:17:39,600
Ok. Have you ever heard
of the midnight circle?

269
00:17:39,707 --> 00:17:42,702
- Knitting club for insomniacs?
- You're hilarious. Yes or no?

270
00:17:42,806 --> 00:17:45,002
No.

271
00:17:45,206 --> 00:17:47,200
No? That's it?

272
00:17:47,308 --> 00:17:50,202
Wait, there's no medieval
significance or minutiae?

273
00:17:50,306 --> 00:17:53,501
Uh, oh! No.
I don't know anything about it.

274
00:17:53,608 --> 00:17:55,401
- Ok, then.
- I have a picture to hang.

275
00:17:55,506 --> 00:17:57,900
Great.

276
00:18:02,905 --> 00:18:06,800
You know, if you do ever want to talk,

277
00:18:06,905 --> 00:18:10,502
I'm a really good listener.

278
00:18:11,006 --> 00:18:14,402
I don't know if I have
any training for that.

279
00:18:14,506 --> 00:18:17,001
Yeah, I didn't think so.

280
00:18:17,105 --> 00:18:20,103
Keep it in mind.

281
00:22:40,008 --> 00:22:41,800
I can't believe you lied to me.

282
00:22:41,907 --> 00:22:44,302
It was a secret.
I had to promise I wouldn't tell.

283
00:22:44,405 --> 00:22:46,002
And that was the midnight circle?
There's nothing else?

284
00:22:46,106 --> 00:22:48,200
'Cause no more games, Ned.

285
00:22:48,305 --> 00:22:51,100
It's a race, a couple of times a month.

286
00:22:51,208 --> 00:22:54,600
They race for money, pink slips,
stuff like that.

287
00:22:54,707 --> 00:22:59,603
- And there aren't any rules.
- Where does your mom think you are?

288
00:22:59,707 --> 00:23:01,103
In bed.

289
00:23:01,207 --> 00:23:03,700
I climbed out the window.

290
00:23:03,805 --> 00:23:07,900
You have no idea
how much trouble you're in.

291
00:23:08,007 --> 00:23:10,502
Delia was furious.
I mean, she was so embarrassed.

292
00:23:10,607 --> 00:23:13,503
Here she is thinking that her
son is asleep in his bedroom.

293
00:23:13,608 --> 00:23:16,600
I thought you said you weren't going to
go out on that road again without me.

294
00:23:16,708 --> 00:23:19,600
I had to go when I had the chance.

295
00:23:19,708 --> 00:23:23,800
- Is that where you saw the ghost?
- Yeah. He was in the car that crashed.

296
00:23:23,906 --> 00:23:26,502
- You think he caused it?
- I don't know what to think.

297
00:23:26,608 --> 00:23:30,901
I mean, I know that the ghost
is attached to this world,
but it's all so secret.

298
00:23:31,008 --> 00:23:34,202
You should have seen the way they all
scattered when they heard the sirens.

299
00:23:34,306 --> 00:23:35,801
You think he's trying
to hurt the racers?

300
00:23:35,907 --> 00:23:40,702
Yeah. And I'm really worried
about Cindy, because he said
that somebody's going to die.

301
00:23:40,806 --> 00:23:43,103
Maybe that's the way
he died--in a crash.

302
00:23:43,205 --> 00:23:45,803
I keep checking online,
but I don't have a lot to go on.

303
00:23:45,905 --> 00:23:47,702
I don't know his name.
I don't know what he looked like.

304
00:23:47,806 --> 00:23:49,901
I don't know when he died.

305
00:23:50,005 --> 00:23:53,501
I'll check the records at work,
ask around.

306
00:23:53,606 --> 00:23:56,303
Look, no offense.
It's just not something we talk about.

307
00:23:56,406 --> 00:23:58,500
Yeah, I understand,
but people may get hurt.

308
00:23:58,608 --> 00:24:00,202
That's half the thrill
of the whole thing.

309
00:24:00,307 --> 00:24:03,301
- For some people.
- Ok, you almost got killed last night.

310
00:24:03,407 --> 00:24:06,701
Last night? I don't think so.
I was at home in bed last night.

311
00:24:06,806 --> 00:24:10,801
I don't know what you're talking about.
Sorry. Um, Melissa, is it?

312
00:24:10,908 --> 00:24:12,603
Melinda.

313
00:24:12,707 --> 00:24:15,500
Yeah, well, I got to run.
There's coffee and pastry in the breakroom.

314
00:24:15,607 --> 00:24:19,803
Help yourself.
Thanks for coming by.

315
00:24:43,508 --> 00:24:46,601
He died in an illegal street race
19th of february last year

316
00:24:46,706 --> 00:24:49,102
in the same spot where
my car first broke down.

317
00:24:49,208 --> 00:24:53,201
It says he owned Pike custom owners.
He was racing a guy named Ray Peters.

318
00:24:53,308 --> 00:24:55,202
There were no charges filed.
There's nothing else.

319
00:24:55,308 --> 00:24:56,702
Look at the bottom.

320
00:24:56,806 --> 00:25:01,003
Survived by his fiancee Cindy Brown.

321
00:25:01,106 --> 00:25:02,700
- Cindy Cindy.
- Exactly.

322
00:25:02,806 --> 00:25:05,201
Now I know who the ghost is
and who he's attached to.

323
00:25:05,308 --> 00:25:07,802
- What's he trying to do?
- Protect her? I don't know.

324
00:25:07,907 --> 00:25:10,502
Maybe he's going to wipe out
all the people who race against her?

325
00:25:10,608 --> 00:25:13,102
Sounds like a true romantic.

326
00:25:13,207 --> 00:25:17,001
- All right, what are you going to do?
- I've got to find this ghost tonight.

327
00:25:17,106 --> 00:25:19,502
You doing anything?

328
00:25:19,608 --> 00:25:21,903
Cool.

329
00:25:27,306 --> 00:25:30,402
Just, uh, stay in the beam
of the headlight.

330
00:25:30,507 --> 00:25:34,303
Yeah. I'll wave if I need you.

331
00:25:44,205 --> 00:25:46,801
I know your name.

332
00:25:46,906 --> 00:25:49,603
Gordon Pike.

333
00:25:49,706 --> 00:25:52,901
I know that you died in a car race.

334
00:25:53,008 --> 00:25:55,701
I can help.

335
00:25:56,208 --> 00:26:00,103
I think I know what's going on.

336
00:26:00,906 --> 00:26:05,200
This has to do with Cindy, doesn't it?

337
00:26:11,408 --> 00:26:14,002
Yeah, it's about Cindy.

338
00:26:14,105 --> 00:26:16,300
Well, I can help you
talk to her if you want,

339
00:26:16,406 --> 00:26:19,501
if it'll help you cross over,
but you can't stay here.

340
00:26:19,607 --> 00:26:23,302
- You just can't. 
- I trained her, taught her to race.

341
00:26:23,407 --> 00:26:26,203
Everything she knows is because of me.

342
00:26:26,305 --> 00:26:28,501
Yeah, but that doesn't mean
you can protect her forever.

343
00:26:28,605 --> 00:26:30,901
I don't want to protect her.

344
00:26:31,008 --> 00:26:34,302
I'm going to kill her.

345
00:26:34,906 --> 00:26:38,701
She thought she was as good as me.
She wanted to prove she was better.

346
00:26:38,807 --> 00:26:42,100
I don't understand. I thought you two
were a couple. Weren't you engaged?

347
00:26:42,206 --> 00:26:45,800
I was her first love.
She thought I was a rock star.

348
00:26:45,905 --> 00:26:48,703
Most  people were afraid of me
because I wanted to race.

349
00:26:48,807 --> 00:26:50,201
Not her.

350
00:26:50,306 --> 00:26:52,701
I've never had anybody
look at me that way before.

351
00:26:52,807 --> 00:26:56,203
Ok, so what went wrong?

352
00:26:56,507 --> 00:26:58,703
I let her drive my car.

353
00:26:58,905 --> 00:27:00,502
What?

354
00:27:00,607 --> 00:27:03,802
I taught her to race.
I showed her everything I know.

355
00:27:03,907 --> 00:27:06,603
She was good, too.
A natural.

356
00:27:06,707 --> 00:27:08,901
Then she didn't need me anymore.

357
00:27:09,008 --> 00:27:12,601
She wanted to prove
she was faster and smarter.

358
00:27:12,706 --> 00:27:16,303
- Was she?
- Smarter, maybe.

359
00:27:16,407 --> 00:27:19,502
She really knew how to mess
with my head before a race.

360
00:27:19,608 --> 00:27:23,001
It started with just kid stuff.
She's got to competitive with me.

361
00:27:23,106 --> 00:27:25,701
Then she had to keep pushing it.

362
00:27:25,805 --> 00:27:29,002
- Like, sometimes she'd mess
with my nitrous. - Nitrous?

363
00:27:29,107 --> 00:27:32,802
You inject it into the manifold
when you need a last-second boost.

364
00:27:32,908 --> 00:27:35,401
Or she'd mess with my fuel mixture.
Little things.

365
00:27:35,506 --> 00:27:39,701
But then I started losing,
and it wasn't funny anymore.

366
00:27:39,808 --> 00:27:44,900
The night I died was a big race between
me and Ray Peters, a 15k payday.

367
00:27:45,005 --> 00:27:48,002
And she warned me she wasn't going
to let me get paid that night.

368
00:27:48,106 --> 00:27:49,601
So, what happened?

369
00:27:49,706 --> 00:27:53,302
I came out of the turn, hit the nitrous button.

370
00:27:53,405 --> 00:27:57,002
Next thing I know... boom!

371
00:28:00,605 --> 00:28:05,202
I'm floating above my car watching it burn.

372
00:28:05,605 --> 00:28:08,802
And I see my body just laying there,

373
00:28:08,908 --> 00:28:12,300
all the skin burned off.

374
00:28:13,408 --> 00:28:16,300
Do you really think that Cindy
could do something like that?

375
00:28:16,408 --> 00:28:19,000
Maybe, maybe not.
Same result.

376
00:28:19,108 --> 00:28:21,402
She took things too far.

377
00:28:21,508 --> 00:28:24,703
Did you cause the crash the other night?

378
00:28:24,808 --> 00:28:30,801
I was just having some fun,
making Jimmy bash her around a little.

379
00:28:32,206 --> 00:28:35,102
I'm saving the real thing for monday.

380
00:28:35,206 --> 00:28:37,403
The 19th of february.

381
00:28:37,508 --> 00:28:41,201
The day you died, a year ago.

382
00:28:43,008 --> 00:28:45,201
Well, I'm sorry.
I don't mean to make fun.

383
00:28:45,307 --> 00:28:48,302
No, it's ok. I'm used to people
being in tears right about now.

384
00:28:48,407 --> 00:28:52,103
I can just picture Gordon running around
like a ghost, still trying to win races.

385
00:28:52,208 --> 00:28:54,400
What a funny idea.

386
00:28:54,507 --> 00:28:55,501
You know I'm not kidding.

387
00:28:55,605 --> 00:28:58,702
Oh, no. You seem like you really believe it.

388
00:28:58,807 --> 00:29:02,500
He told me that he made Jimmy
run into your car.

389
00:29:02,606 --> 00:29:03,800
What do you want?

390
00:29:03,905 --> 00:29:05,503
I think Gordon's trying to hurt you.

391
00:29:05,607 --> 00:29:09,003
Well, he couldn't do that anymore
than he already has.

392
00:29:09,108 --> 00:29:11,503
He told me that he taught you
everything about racing.

393
00:29:11,606 --> 00:29:13,500
He did. But once I got the hang of it,

394
00:29:13,605 --> 00:29:15,900
I could make a car do
any damn thing I wanted.

395
00:29:16,007 --> 00:29:17,800
My very first race I won.

396
00:29:17,905 --> 00:29:21,202
Then I won the next one and
the one after that. It was crazy.

397
00:29:21,306 --> 00:29:25,902
Right away, people started
to know my name.

398
00:29:31,007 --> 00:29:32,602
Gordon got so jealous.

399
00:29:32,706 --> 00:29:35,902
He still thought he was better than me,
and he never let me forget it.

400
00:29:36,007 --> 00:29:38,501
He even got a car straight from
Japan with right-hand drive--

401
00:29:38,608 --> 00:29:40,800
anything to get attention.

402
00:29:40,906 --> 00:29:44,503
So, naturally,
I'd challenge him,

403
00:29:44,607 --> 00:29:46,000
and I'd beat him.

404
00:29:46,105 --> 00:29:48,203
Over and over again.

405
00:29:48,307 --> 00:29:51,103
I wasn't just Gordon Pike's
girlfriend anymore.

406
00:29:51,207 --> 00:29:54,303
He was Cindy Brown's boyfriend.

407
00:29:54,408 --> 00:29:57,200
- He said he was your first love.
- Oh, he was.

408
00:29:57,305 --> 00:29:59,703
He was everything I thought
a man was supposed to be.

409
00:29:59,806 --> 00:30:02,302
And then he showed me what I could do.
He showed me what was possible.

410
00:30:02,408 --> 00:30:06,602
I mean, I never thought I had any kind
of talent, let alone this kind.

411
00:30:06,706 --> 00:30:09,001
- Just one problem.
- What?

412
00:30:09,108 --> 00:30:13,001
Once he saw how good I was, he wanted
to put the genie back in the bottle.

413
00:30:13,107 --> 00:30:14,401
Like how?

414
00:30:14,507 --> 00:30:17,200
He'd do anything to keep
guys from racing me.

415
00:30:17,305 --> 00:30:19,703
What happened the night he died?

416
00:30:19,808 --> 00:30:22,902
Gordon was pissed. Ray Peters
had never been beaten before.

417
00:30:23,006 --> 00:30:27,103
He had to wait in line to race him.

418
00:30:27,306 --> 00:30:29,000
Me and you, finally.

419
00:30:29,105 --> 00:30:33,003
- Man, I'm shaking.
- Yeah, you will be.

420
00:30:33,106 --> 00:30:35,900
You're the one I should be racing,
not your old man.

421
00:30:36,006 --> 00:30:38,803
You're the one to beat,
from what I hear.

422
00:30:38,905 --> 00:30:42,100
Yeah, well, you have to
get past him first.

423
00:30:42,207 --> 00:30:44,800
Done deal.

424
00:30:48,408 --> 00:30:52,101
He was out of control after that,
and I guess I wasn't much comfort.

425
00:30:52,207 --> 00:30:53,500
What do you mean?

426
00:30:53,607 --> 00:30:55,000
I liked it.

427
00:30:55,108 --> 00:30:56,401
I liked that Ray said what he said.

428
00:30:56,507 --> 00:31:00,901
Hell, it was more of a compliment
than I ever got from Gordon.

429
00:31:01,007 --> 00:31:05,503
He thinks that you did something to
his car to cause the crash that night.

430
00:31:05,608 --> 00:31:07,601
I had nothing to do with
what happened to Gordon.

431
00:31:07,708 --> 00:31:09,603
Ray Peters ran him off the track.
Everyone knows that.

432
00:31:09,708 --> 00:31:12,702
- So, Ray Peters caused the accident?
- The king of dirty tricks?

433
00:31:12,805 --> 00:31:15,100
He probably did it just coming out
of the turn where no one could see.

434
00:31:15,206 --> 00:31:19,701
- Yeah, but Gordon's car blew up.
- Look!

435
00:31:19,906 --> 00:31:25,001
I did love Gordon, even when
I hated him. You understand?

436
00:31:25,107 --> 00:31:26,600
Not really, no.

437
00:31:26,705 --> 00:31:30,603
I would never have done anything
to hurt Gordon. Not like that.

438
00:31:30,708 --> 00:31:36,101
And if he is really here
like you say he is, he knows it.

439
00:31:39,805 --> 00:31:41,501
I feel like I've gone from
"West Side Story" to

440
00:31:41,608 --> 00:31:43,902
- "Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf."
- It's just so weird.

441
00:31:44,006 --> 00:31:46,701
Two people who start out loving
each other end up hating each other.

442
00:31:46,806 --> 00:31:47,501
How does that happen?

443
00:31:47,608 --> 00:31:50,002
The question you gotta ask is
why do they keep making it happen.

444
00:31:50,106 --> 00:31:51,102
What do you mean?

445
00:31:51,205 --> 00:31:53,403
Well, I mean, everybody's
got a storeroom, right?

446
00:31:53,507 --> 00:31:55,800
Resentment, grudges, anger?

447
00:31:55,908 --> 00:31:58,600
Most people, they open up that storeroom
and they let a few of them out.

448
00:31:58,707 --> 00:32:00,800
You know, they deal with them.
They get rid of them.

449
00:32:00,907 --> 00:32:04,700
Something tells me that your storeroom
would be standing room only.

450
00:32:04,806 --> 00:32:07,103
Yeah, sometimes i gotta knock down
the wall into the next storeroom,

451
00:32:07,206 --> 00:32:11,101
but the point is, you know, a couple,
two people, they start using those bad

452
00:32:11,206 --> 00:32:14,202
things from that storeroom
against each other, why stay?

453
00:32:14,306 --> 00:32:15,100
Why not move on?

454
00:32:15,205 --> 00:32:16,900
Maybe they're getting
something out of it.

455
00:32:17,008 --> 00:32:19,001
Yeah. They need to be miserable.

456
00:32:19,107 --> 00:32:21,601
For some people, that's as strong
as the need to breath.

457
00:32:21,706 --> 00:32:23,501
It's like they're feeding off
each other, like they're trying

458
00:32:23,606 --> 00:32:28,500
to convince each other that
they don't deserve to be happy.

459
00:32:28,608 --> 00:32:31,700
Makes me glad I'm basically a simpleton.

460
00:32:31,806 --> 00:32:33,703
Far from it.

461
00:32:33,806 --> 00:32:36,903
You gotta keep these two people
away from each other for good.

462
00:32:37,007 --> 00:32:38,801
How are you going to do that?

463
00:32:38,906 --> 00:32:41,700
I'm going to talk to a guy
named Ray Peters.

464
00:32:41,807 --> 00:32:43,503
Now you want me
to hang out with racers?

465
00:32:43,605 --> 00:32:46,801
What I want is for you to introduce me
to Ray Peters. It's important.

466
00:32:46,908 --> 00:32:49,601
- Ghost related?
- Yeah, if you must know.

467
00:32:49,707 --> 00:32:52,703
- I like to be kept a little more
in the loop. - You're unbelievable.

468
00:32:52,805 --> 00:32:54,301
You could just think of me
as a sounding board.

469
00:32:54,407 --> 00:32:56,801
Look, are you going to introduce me
to Ray Peters or not?

470
00:32:56,905 --> 00:32:59,402
Are you going to save me from
my mother hanging me by my ankles?

471
00:32:59,505 --> 00:33:01,400
You're lucky to have a mother
who cares so much about you,

472
00:33:01,505 --> 00:33:04,303
and we are not going
anywhere near cars.

473
00:33:04,406 --> 00:33:08,503
Do you know where Ray Peters works?

